BOT FIX V2

Document type: UX remediation notes and implementation spec
Date: 2026-03-04
Project: reminder_bot

0. Deterministic conventions (mandatory for this document)
1. "Now/current time" always means `datetime.now(user_timezone)`.
2. All date/time comparisons are performed in user timezone, not UTC.
3. Callback/session mismatch is always treated as stale session.
4. Phase execution gate is strict:
   next phase starts only after previous phase is fully green (tests + acceptance checks).
5. If implementation behavior is not explicitly described here, it must not be invented ad hoc:
   missing rule must be added to this document first.
6. Legacy policy:
   old logic must be removed during implementation of each phase; parallel old/new execution paths are forbidden.
7. Input contract:
   user enters free text only for activity; date/time are selected only via buttons (no manual date/time parsing).

1. Current UX status
1. UX is significantly better than legacy version (calendar, browser list, edit/clone/delete/undo exist).
2. Current practical rating: 7.5/10.
3. Main remaining friction is not core functionality, but context continuity and predictability of user flow.

2. Confirmed UX issues
1. Context loss after operations:
   create/edit/clone flows often end in MAIN_MENU instead of returning user to current browser page/filter.
2. Weak cancel behavior in duplicate warning:
   pressing cancel in dup2 flow can leave user without explicit visual return to prior screen.
3. Manual time parsing is too broad:
   natural phrases are still accepted in manual mode (for strict UX this is undesirable).
4. Week filter semantics ambiguity:
   "Неделя" currently means "now -> Sunday", which may not match user expectation ("7 days" or "Mon-Sun").
5. Regression risk:
   current test coverage is strong, but missing explicit tests for context return after mutation actions.
6. Notes field overload:
   extra "Заметки/Примечание" step increases friction and is not required by product target.

3. Required UX fixes (implementation order)

PHASE A: Browser context continuity (mandatory)
1. Preserve browser context for all browser-originated operations:
   edit, clone, delete, undo.
2. Store in FSM:
   return_to_browser=true,
   browser_sid,
   browser_filter,
   browser_page,
   browser_message_id.
3. On successful mutation, refresh the same browser message using existing refresh helper.
4. Do not send user to MAIN_MENU when action was initiated from browser.
5. If browser message cannot be edited (deleted/not found), send one new browser message and update FSM `browser_message_id`.
6. If browser context in FSM is missing/corrupted, fallback to MAIN_MENU with explicit error text.
7. Acceptance:
   after edit/clone/delete/undo user stays on same filter/page and sees updated list.

PHASE B: Deterministic cancel in duplicate-warning (mandatory)
1. For all dup2 cancel actions:
   create flow -> return to create confirmation preview.
   edit datetime flow -> return to edit field menu.
   clone flow -> return to clone confirmation preview.
2. Add explicit message update/answer on cancel; no silent no-op.
3. Cancel action must never clear flow data needed for immediate return screen.
4. Acceptance:
   every cancel produces predictable visible state transition.

PHASE C: Time input redesign without WebApp (mandatory)
Goal:
Replace free-form manual time step with inline pseudo-roller in regular Telegram bot UI.
Manual time text input is fully removed.

1. UI layout (single editable message):
   [-1ч] [HH] [+1ч]
   [-5м] [MM] [+5м]
   [00] [15] [30] [45]
   [Сейчас+1ч] [Готово] [Отмена]

2. Behavior:
1. All controls update one message via edit_text/edit_reply_markup.
2. HH wraps in range 00..23.
3. MM wraps in range 00..59.
4. [00][15][30][45] sets minutes directly in current hour.
5. [Сейчас+1ч] sets candidate time to now+1 hour in user timezone.
6. [Готово] validates candidate datetime against selected date and user timezone.
7. If selected datetime <= now, reject with explicit error and keep picker open.
8. [Отмена] exits picker and returns to previous deterministic screen.
9. Picker initial value is mandatory:
   when picker opens, HH:MM is prefilled from current user local time.
10. Picker reopen rule:
   each new open of picker within any flow (create/edit/clone) again initializes HH:MM from current user local time.
11. Existing candidate time is preserved only when user stays on same picker message and presses +/- or preset minute buttons.

3. Callback protocol (recommended):
1. tmr2:<sid>:h:minus1
2. tmr2:<sid>:h:plus1
3. tmr2:<sid>:m:minus5
4. tmr2:<sid>:m:plus5
5. tmr2:<sid>:m:set:00|15|30|45
6. tmr2:<sid>:quick:now_plus_1h
7. tmr2:<sid>:ok
8. tmr2:<sid>:cancel

4. FSM data:
1. time_picker_sid
2. time_picker_message_id
3. tp_hour
4. tp_minute
5. selected_date_iso
6. timezone
7. return_to_browser + browser context keys if launched from browser.
8. selected_date_iso is mandatory before picker open; if missing -> explicit stale error and flow restart prompt.

5. Integration points:
1. create flow (wizard)
2. edit datetime flow (event_edit)
3. clone datetime flow (task_browser)

6. Manual text policy (mandatory):
1. Remove natural-language parsing from all time states.
2. Remove strict HH:MM text fallback from all time states.
3. Time is selected only via picker buttons and quick-time buttons.
4. Any text received while waiting for time must return explicit guidance:
   "Выберите время кнопками."
5. Date is selected only via calendar buttons.
6. Any text received while waiting for date must return explicit guidance:
   "Выберите дату кнопками календаря."

PHASE D: Week filter semantics hardening (mandatory)
1. Choose one fixed definition and keep it everywhere:
   Selected and final: next 7 days from current moment (rolling window now..now+7d).
2. Boundary contract:
   lower bound inclusive (`>= now`), upper bound inclusive (`<= now+7d`).
3. Update:
   filter bounds logic,
   browser header text,
   tests for boundaries.
4. Acceptance:
   semantics documented and fully deterministic for timezone-aware users.

